Interesting! A linter modified `globals.css`. The Tailwind CSS v4 tooling (or postcss) changed the CSS to use CSS variables more correctly. The change is:

Instead of:
```css
.dark {
  --color-falcon-bg: #0f172a;
  ...
}
```

It changed to:
```css
@theme {
  ...
  --color-falcon-bg: var(--falcon-bg);
  ...
}

.dark {
  --falcon-bg: #0f172a;
  ...
}
```

This is actually a proper Tailwind CSS v4 pattern! The `@theme` block defines the *design token* variables (`--color-falcon-*`) that reference theme variables (`--falcon-*`). 

The `.dark` and `.light` blocks now set the underlying theme variables instead of the design tokens directly. This means my tests are going to fail since they're looking for `--color-falcon-bg` in those blocks, but the actual variable being set is now `--falcon-bg`.

I need to decide whether to revert the linter's changes or update my tests to match the new CSS structure that the Tailwind v4 postcss tooling generated. Let me check the current state of globals.css to see exactly what changed.

